                <head>48. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In early September 1953 <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> officers met with the
                    man known to be <persName corresp="#p_CACC1">Castillo Armas</persName>’ main
                    ally inside of Guatemala City. The information received by the <gloss
                        target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> in New York on September 6–7 differed from the
                    assessment of internal support described in <ref target="#d47">Document
                    47</ref>. According to the source, there already were 53,000 anti-Communist
                    Guatemalans organized in cells of 315 men inside the country, approximately
                    8,000 supporters within 1 hour of the capital, and two functional intelligence
                    nets. Other assets listed by the source included five clandestine radio stations
                    and ample supplies for the manufacture of bombs. He noted, however: “Capture of
                    Guatemala City at the outset of the movement will require the immobilization or
                    assassination of the key civilian members of the Government as well as
                    immobilization of a majority of the officers.”</p>
                <p>At the conclusion of the meeting, the source agreed that his organization would
                    prepare a detailed plan and timetable while the <gloss target="#t_CIA1"
                        >CIA</gloss> would provide 8–10 tons of arms for training purposes.
                    (Memorandum for the Record, September 8; Central Intelligence Agency, Job
                    79–01025A, Box 151, Folder 7)</p>
            </div>
